### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

Host property on Angular Component decorator doesnt apply more than one class. @HostBinding works fine. 

Code example:

This works just fine. Every class is an element of an array. even the calculated one is ok. 

  host: {
    '[class]': `['flex', 'max-w-max', orientation === 'row' && !reversed ? 'flex-row': '',]`,
  },

However this doesn't work. Two classes in a string are not added to element class:

  host: {
    '[class]': `['bg-primary p-10']`,
  },

When used with @HostBinding works just fine:

 @HostBinding('attr.class')
  get Classes() {
    return ['bg-primary p-10']
  }
  
  Same story happens with strings returned by functions:

 host: {    '[class]': `[getOrientationDirection(orientation), getOrientationAlign(orientation), getGap(elementGap)]`,  },

This works, as long as each returns ONLY ONE class, for example:

 getOrientationDirection(orientation: AppFlexDirection) {
    if (orientation === 'row') {
      return 'flex-row';
    }
    return '';
  }

When returning 2 classes it doesnt work. So after extensive testing i came into conclusion, that the implementation of host is not working very well with tailwind, however @HostBinding works just fine, however its now a legacy feature, cant be fully replaced by host at this point.



